We have a pattern for types that implement a comparer interface (e.g.:  `IEqualityComparer<T>`):  implement a static property that returns an instance of the comparer.  That way, comparisons do not require instantiating a new comparer.  Unfortunately, this pattern was incorrectly implemented.

These properties will return a new instance every time the property is accessed:

```C#
public static MyComparer Instance { get { return new MyComparer(); } }
public static MyComparer Instance { get => new MyComparer(); }
```

This will return the same instance every time the property is accessed:

```C#
public static MyComparer Instance { get; } = new MyComparer();
```

